âœ… 1. Network Security Groups (NSG)
ğŸ“Œ What is NSG?

NSG is a firewall-like feature that controls inbound and outbound traffic to/from Azure resources.
It uses rules to allow or deny traffic based on:
Source (IP, range, or tag)
Destination (IP, range, or tag)
Protocol (TCP, UDP, ICMP)
Port Range
Action (Allow/Deny)
You can associate NSGs with:
Subnets
Network Interfaces (NICs)
âœ… 2. NSG Rules and Priorities
ğŸ“Œ NSG rules control traffic flow and have the following characteristics:

Default Rules:
Automatically created by Azure (cannot be deleted).
Examples:
Allow VNet-Inbound â†’ Allows communication between resources in the same VNet.
Allow Azure Load Balancer-Inbound â†’ Allows health probes from Azure load balancers.
Deny All-Inbound and Outbound â†’ Blocks all traffic not explicitly allowed.
Custom Rules:
Created by users.
Define specific allow/deny rules.
Rules are evaluated in order of priority (lower numbers = higher priority).
âœ… Rule evaluation logic:

Lowest priority number is evaluated first.
If traffic matches a rule, subsequent rules are ignored.
âœ… 3. Application Security Groups (ASG)
ğŸ“Œ What is ASG?

ASG allows you to group VMs or NICs into logical groups.
Benefits over NSG:
Simplifies management of complex environments.
You donâ€™t need to reference specific IPs â€“ use ASG instead.
Easier to scale: Add/remove VMs from ASG without modifying NSG rules.
âœ… Use Case Example:

Create Web-ASG, App-ASG, and DB-ASG.
Allow only web servers to talk to app servers and only app servers to talk to the database.
This improves segmentation and security without managing individual IPs.
âœ… 4. DDoS Protection
ğŸ“Œ What is DDoS Protection?

DDoS (Distributed Denial-of-Service) protection secures Azure resources from large-scale attacks.
Azure offers:
Basic (Free) â†’ Enabled by default.
Standard (Paid) â†’ Advanced protection with monitoring, mitigation, and alerts.
âœ… Key Differences:

Feature	Basic	Standard
Protection Scope	Default protection	Advanced protection
Mitigation	Automatic	Custom policy mitigation
Traffic Analytics	None	Yes
Alerts	No	Yes
Cost	Free	Billable
âœ… 5. Hands-on: NSG & ASG in Azure Portal + CLI
ğŸ”¥ Part 1: Create NSG and Associate with Subnets
ğŸ› ï¸ Steps via Azure Portal:
Go to Azure Portal â†’ Networking â†’ Network Security Groups
Click + Create
Enter the details:
NSG Name: MyNSG
Region: Same as your VNet
Resource Group: Use the same one as your VNet
Click Review + Create â†’ Create
âœ… Add Inbound Rule:
Go to Inbound Security Rules â†’ + Add
Configure the rule:
Name: Allow-SSH
Priority: 100
Source: Any
Destination: Any
Protocol: TCP
Port range: 22
Action: Allow
Click Add
âœ… Associate NSG with Subnet:
Go to Settings â†’ Subnets â†’ Associate
Select the VNet and subnet
Click Save
ğŸ”¥ Part 2: Create ASG and Associate with VMs
ğŸ› ï¸ Steps via Azure Portal:
Go to Azure Portal â†’ Networking â†’ Application Security Groups
Click + Create
Enter the details:
ASG Name: Web-ASG
Region: Same as your VNet
Resource Group: Use the same one
Click Review + Create â†’ Create
âœ… Assign ASG to a VM:
Go to Virtual Machines â†’ Select VM
Click Networking
Select + Configure ASG
Select Web-ASG â†’ Save
âœ… Final Result:

Youâ€™ve created an NSG with rules and associated it with a subnet.
Youâ€™ve created an ASG and linked it to a VM.
âœ… 6. Terraform: Deploy NSGs & ASGs via Infrastructure as Code
ğŸ”¥ Terraform Configuration:
Create a directory for NSG & ASG:
bash
Copy
Edit
mkdir nsg-asg-terraform
cd nsg-asg-terraform
Create the main.tf file:
bash
Copy
Edit
nano main.tf
Add the following configuration:
hcl
Copy
Edit
# Provider
provider "azurerm" {
  features {}
}

# NSG
resource "azurerm_network_security_group" "nsg" {
  name                = "MyNSG"
  location            = "East US"
  resource_group_name = "MyVNetRG"

  security_rule {
    name                       = "Allow-SSH"
    priority                   = 100
    direction                  = "Inbound"
    access                     = "Allow"
    protocol                   = "Tcp"
    source_port_range          = "*"
    destination_port_range     = "22"
    source_address_prefix      = "*"
    destination_address_prefix = "*"
  }
}

# ASG
resource "azurerm_application_security_group" "asg" {
  name                = "Web-ASG"
  location            = "East US"
  resource_group_name = "MyVNetRG"
}
Initialize Terraform:
bash
Copy
Edit
terraform init
Plan the Deployment:
bash
Copy
Edit
terraform plan
Apply the Deployment:
bash
Copy
Edit
terraform apply
âœ… Output:

NSG with rules and ASG will be created.
Verify in Azure Portal.
âœ… 7. Troubleshooting Common NSG Issues
âœ… 1. NSG Rules Not Working:

Check Rule Priorities: Lower number = higher priority.
Check Effective Security Rules:
Go to VM â†’ Networking â†’ Effective Security Rules to view applied rules.
âœ… 2. Ping/SSH Still Blocked:

Make sure you allowed the required ports (e.g., 22, 3389, 80, etc.).
âœ… 3. NSG Association Issues:

Ensure the NSG is properly associated with the Subnet or NIC.
